Female.
(
Fig. 68
). Typical of genus. Subgenital plate well-developed, subtriangular in shape; base broad, extending from posterior of seventh sternum entirely over eighth sternum and approximately ¼ over ninth sternum; apical portion darker than basal portion, terminating in broadly-rounded apex (
Fig. 68
).

Etymology. This species is named in honor of the late Dr. Andrew Sheldon. Andy was a close working colleague of both authors and was responsible for collecting the first series of specimens of this new species. Mountain Man Forestfly is proposed as the common name for this species (
Stark et al . 2012
).
